05270nam a22008415i 9780231549912DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018047977  a97802315499127 a10.7312/mcaf192682doi  a(DE-B1597)526819  a(OCoLC)1101800870  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC423b.M1265 2019 7aPHI0400002bisacsh04a320.012231 aMcAfee, Noëlle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFear of Breakdown :bPolitics and Psychoanalysis /cNoëlle McAfee. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in Critical Theory ;v6500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tBY WAY OF A PREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Defining Politics -- t2. Psychoanalysis and Political Theory -- t3. Politics and the Fear of Breakdown -- t4. Practicing Democracy -- t5. Democratic Imaginaries -- t6. Becoming Citizens -- t7. Definitions of the Situation -- t8. Deliberating Otherwise -- t9. Political Works of Mourning -- t10. Public Will and Action -- t11. Radical Imaginaries -- t12. Nationalism and the Fear of Breakdown -- tConclusion: Working Through Breakdown -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is behind the upsurge of virulent nationalism and intransigent politics across the globe today? In Fear of Breakdown, Noëlle McAfee uses psychoanalytic theory to explore the subterranean anxieties behind current crises and the ways in which democratic practices can help work through seemingly intractable political conflicts. Working at the intersection of psyche and society, McAfee draws on psychoanalyst D. W. Winnicott’s concept of the fear of breakdown to show how hypernationalism stems from unconscious anxieties over the origins of personal and social identities, giving rise to temptations to reify exclusionary phantasies of national origins.Fear of Breakdown contends that politics needs something that only psychoanalysis has been able to offer: an understanding of how to work through anxieties, ambiguity, fragility, and loss in order to create a more democratic politics. Coupling robust psychoanalytic theory with concrete democratic practice, Fear of Breakdown shows how a politics of working through can help counter a politics of splitting, paranoia, and demonization. McAfee argues for a new approach to deliberative democratic theory, not the usual philosopher-sanctioned process of reason-giving but an affective process of making difficult choices, encountering others, and mourning what cannot be had.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCritical theory. 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aDemocracyxPsychological aspects. 0aDemocracy-Psychological aspects. 0aPolitical psychology. 0aPsychoanalysisxPolitical aspects. 0aPsychoanalysis-Political aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mcaf1926840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231549912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231549912/original  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economic